</article>
   <article class="item has-image has-audio">
    <div class="item-image">
        <div class="imagewrap" data-crop-type="wide">
    <a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/04/13/826474975/coronavirus-nurses-ask-an-ebola-veteran-is-it-ok-to-be-afraid" data-metrics='{"action":"Click Story Image","category":"Story List"}' >
        <img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/13/martha-7_wide-a830242c8b45efe37664db5f422d791b5b8bd660-s300-c15.jpg" data-original="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2020/04/13/martha-7_wide-a830242c8b45efe37664db5f422d791b5b8bd660-s300.jpg" class="respArchListImg lazyOnLoad"  alt="Coronavirus Nurses Ask An Ebola Veteran: Is It OK To Be Afraid?" />
    </a>
</div>
<div class="credit-caption">
    <div class="caption-wrap">
        <div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption">
            <p>
                In 2014, Martha Phillips, an American nurse, traveled to West Africa during the Ebola crisis to provide medical care. Treating Ebola not only taught her how to stay safe around a deadly virus but also how to manage the stress and sadness of working during a disease outbreak. She's now drawing on that experience to help other nurses cope with the challenges of coronavirus.
                
                <b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit">
                    
                    Martha Phillips
                    
                </b>
                <b class="hide-caption"><b>hide caption</b></b>
            </p>
